values:
Once long ago, there was an older woman who lived in a very small house on a hill. Everyone knew her simply as &quot;Grandma Fishstick&quot;. Grandma Fishstick was the grandmother of four children, appropriately named 1, 2, 3 and X. Every night, the four children would gather at Grandma Fishstick's house to eat dinner, and every night the children were served the same dish: Fishsticks. Like all foods, fishsticks are OK at first. However, after awhile the same exact food will become so tiresome that it cannot continue to be eaten (as a matter of fact, one would probably rather eat fried vomit once in a while). Because of this same unavoidable inclination to dislike a food that one has been forcefed for an extended period of time, the children began to contemplate a rebellion against Grandma Fishstick's cooking endeavors. One Day, the eldest child, Child 1, gathered up the courage to ask Grandma Fishstick why she never served anything for dinner except for fishsticks.

Grandma Fishstick looked at Child 1 and inquired:&quot;Child 1, do you mean to tell me that you no longer love my fishsticks, which I have worked hard to create for you so dearly and so tenderly?&quot;

There was a long silence, as Child 1 pondered this. He finally replied: &quot;Dearest Grandma Fishstick, it is just that we have been eating fishsticks for the past 3 years now, and I would really enjoy something else to eat for dinner...perhaps a stuffed quail? I am very very tired of eating fishsticks. I actually have developed quite a distaste for them!&quot;

Grandma Fishstick's expression became blank. Her face then contorted, and she said: &quot;Come here Child, I have something else for you to eat after all.&quot;

With that, Grandma Fishstick took Child 1 out to her quaint back yard and beat him with a pair of pliers until his siblings had finished eating dinner. Grandma Fishstick then said to Child 1: &quot;I am regretfully aware of the contempt that you hold for my fishsticks, which I have lovingly crafted for your eating delights. From this moment and hereafter, instead of feeding you fishticks for dinner, I will bring you to this very spot and beat you with this same pair of pliers.&quot;


Bewildered and distressed by Grandma Fishstick's sudden anger, Child 1 confided in his siblings, and revealed to them the frightening encounter with Grandma Fishstick. Of course, all of 3 of his siblings were clearly aghast and astonished as Child 1 revealed to them the cuts and bruises he had received during the backyard episode.

As time passed, Child 1 became used to his daily beatings, and his siblings continued to eat fishsticks every day for dinner. After almost a year had passed since the first pliers incident, Child 2 began to contemplate which was the worst of two evils: eating fishsticks every day, or being beaten with a pair of pliers during dinner. On a brisk Thursday night, Child 2 bravely decided to ask the same question his older sibling had asked a year ago. Very predictably, Grandma Fishstick brought Child 2 into the backyard and had him stand in a patch of dry grass next to a dilapidated tool shed. Child 2 fully expected Grandma fishstick come from the shed with a pair of pliers, and trembled in fear when she emerged with a hammer.
